Document: CanvasItem
Path: godot/classes/class_canvasitem.rst
Summary: Covers the extensive set of methods for custom 2D drawing, managing transforms, handling visibility, and querying canvas-related information.

Method: _draw() -> void
Called when CanvasItem has been requested to redraw (after queue_redraw() is called, either manually or by the engine). This is a virtual method. Corresponds to the NOTIFICATION_DRAW notification in Object._notification().

Method: draw_animation_slice(animation_length: float, slice_begin: float, slice_end: float, offset: float = 0.0) -> void
Subsequent drawing commands will be ignored unless they fall within the specified animation slice. This is a faster way to implement animations that loop on background rather than redrawing constantly.

Method: draw_arc(center: Vector2, radius: float, start_angle: float, end_angle: float, point_count: int, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws an unfilled arc between the given angles with a uniform `color` and `width` and optional antialiasing (supported only for positive `width`). The larger the value of `point_count`, the smoother the curve. `center` is defined in local space. For elliptical arcs, see draw_ellipse_arc(). See also draw_circle(). If `width` is negative, it will be ignored and the arc will be drawn using RenderingServer.PRIMITIVE_LINE_STRIP. This means that when the CanvasItem is scaled, the arc will remain thin. If this behavior is not desired, then pass a positive `width` like `1.0`. The arc is drawn from `start_angle` towards the value of `end_angle` so in clockwise direction if `start_angle < end_angle` and counter-clockwise otherwise. Passing the same angles but in reversed order will produce the same arc. If absolute difference of `start_angle` and `end_angle` is greater than @GDScript.TAU radians, then a full circle arc is drawn.

Method: draw_char(font: Font, pos: Vector2, char: String, font_size: int = 16, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Draws a string's first character using a custom font. If `oversampling` is greater than zero, it is used as font oversampling factor, otherwise viewport oversampling settings are used. `pos` is defined in local space.

Method: draw_char_outline(font: Font, pos: Vector2, char: String, font_size: int = 16, size: int = -1, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Draws a string's first character outline using a custom font. If `oversampling` is greater than zero, it is used as font oversampling factor, otherwise viewport oversampling settings are used. `pos` is defined in local space.

Method: draw_circle(position: Vector2, radius: float, color: Color, filled: bool = true, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws a circle, with `position` defined in local space. If `filled` is `true`, the circle will be filled with the `color`. If `false`, it will be drawn as a stroke with the `color` and `width`. If `width` is negative, two-point primitives will be drawn, meaning the lines will remain thin when scaled. Pass a positive `width` like `1.0` to avoid this. If `antialiased` is `true`, outlines will be smooth. Note: `width` is only effective if `filled` is `false`. See also draw_ellipse(), draw_arc(), draw_polyline(), and draw_polygon().

Method: draw_colored_polygon(points: PackedVector2Array, color: Color, uvs: PackedVector2Array = PackedVector2Array(), texture: Texture2D = null) -> void
Draws a colored polygon of any number of points, convex or concave. The points are in local space. Unlike draw_polygon(), a single color must be specified for the whole polygon. Note: If you frequently redraw the same polygon with a large number of vertices, consider pre-calculating the triangulation with Geometry2D.triangulate_polygon() and using draw_mesh(), draw_multimesh(), or RenderingServer.canvas_item_add_triangle_array(). Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, because the drawing operation doesn't begin immediately. Local variables get destroyed before rendering takes place.

Method: draw_dashed_line(from: Vector2, to: Vector2, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, dash: float = 2.0, aligned: bool = true, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws a dashed line between two points in local space. If `width` is negative, the line parts will remain thin when scaled. `dash` is the length of each dash and gap. If `aligned` is `true`, the first and last dashes may be adjusted to fit the line length precisely. If `false`, only full dashes are drawn. If `antialiased` is `true`, outlines are smoothed. Note: `antialiased` is only effective if `width` is greater than `0.0`. See also draw_line(), draw_multiline(), and draw_polyline().

Method: draw_ellipse(position: Vector2, major: float, minor: float, color: Color, filled: bool = true, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws an ellipse with semi-major axis `major` and semi-minor axis `minor`. If `filled` is `true`, it's filled with `color`. If `false`, it's stroked with `color` and `width`. If `width` is negative, lines remain thin when scaled. If `antialiased` is `true`, outlines are smooth. Note: `width` is only effective if `filled` is `false`. See also draw_circle(), draw_ellipse_arc(), draw_polyline(), and draw_polygon().

Method: draw_ellipse_arc(center: Vector2, major: float, minor: float, start_angle: float, end_angle: float, point_count: int, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws an unfilled elliptical arc. The larger `point_count`, the smoother the curve. If `width` is negative, the arc remains thin when scaled. The arc is drawn from `start_angle` towards `end_angle`. If the absolute difference of angles is greater than @GDScript.TAU radians, a full ellipse is drawn. See also draw_arc() and draw_ellipse().

Method: draw_end_animation() -> void
After submitting animation slices via draw_animation_slice(), this function reverts drawing to its default state where all subsequent drawing commands are visible.

Method: draw_lcd_texture_rect_region(texture: Texture2D, rect: Rect2, src_rect: Rect2, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1)) -> void
Draws a textured rectangle region of a font texture with LCD subpixel anti-aliasing. The `rect` is in local space. The blend mode of the CanvasItemMaterial is ignored. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_line(from: Vector2, to: Vector2, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws a line between two points in local space. If `width` is negative, the line remains thin when scaled. See also draw_dashed_line(), draw_multiline(), and draw_polyline().

Method: draw_mesh(mesh: Mesh, texture: Texture2D, transform: Transform2D = Transform2D(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0), modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1)) -> void
Draws a Mesh in 2D, using the provided texture and transform (in local space). Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_msdf_texture_rect_region(texture: Texture2D, rect: Rect2, src_rect: Rect2, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), outline: float = 0.0, pixel_range: float = 4.0, scale: float = 1.0) -> void
Draws a textured rectangle region of a multichannel signed distance field texture. The `rect` is in local space. `pixel_range` should match the value used during texture generation. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_multiline(points: PackedVector2Array, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws multiple disconnected lines with a uniform `width` and `color`. Each line is defined by two consecutive points from the `points` array. This is faster than multiple draw_line() calls. If `width` is negative, lines remain thin when scaled. Note: `antialiased` is only effective if `width` is greater than `0.0`.

Method: draw_multiline_colors(points: PackedVector2Array, colors: PackedColorArray, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws multiple disconnected lines with a uniform `width` and per-segment coloring. Each segment uses a color from the `colors` array. If `width` is negative, lines remain thin when scaled. Note: `antialiased` is only effective if `width` is greater than `0.0`.

Method: draw_multiline_string(font: Font, pos: Vector2, text: String, alignment: HorizontalAlignment = 0, width: float = -1, font_size: int = 16, max_lines: int = -1, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), brk_flags: LineBreakFlag = 3, justification_flags: JustificationFlag = 3, direction: Direction = 0, orientation: Orientation = 0, oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Breaks `text` into lines and draws it using the specified `font` at `pos` (top-left corner) in local space. If `width` is >= 0, text is clipped. `oversampling` overrides viewport settings if > 0.

Method: draw_multiline_string_outline(font: Font, pos: Vector2, text: String, alignment: HorizontalAlignment = 0, width: float = -1, font_size: int = 16, max_lines: int = -1, size: int = 1, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), brk_flags: LineBreakFlag = 3, justification_flags: JustificationFlag = 3, direction: Direction = 0, orientation: Orientation = 0, oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Breaks `text` into lines and draws its outline using the specified `font` at `pos` (top-left corner) in local space. If `width` is >= 0, text is clipped. `oversampling` overrides viewport settings if > 0.

Method: draw_multimesh(multimesh: MultiMesh, texture: Texture2D) -> void
Draws a MultiMesh in 2D with the provided texture. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_polygon(points: PackedVector2Array, colors: PackedColorArray, uvs: PackedVector2Array = PackedVector2Array(), texture: Texture2D = null) -> void
Draws a solid polygon where each point can have a different color. The `points` are in local space. Note: For performance with large polygons, consider pre-calculating triangulation. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_polyline(points: PackedVector2Array, color: Color, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws interconnected line segments with a uniform `color` and `width`. The `points` are in local space. If `width` is negative, the polyline remains thin when scaled.

Method: draw_polyline_colors(points: PackedVector2Array, colors: PackedColorArray, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws interconnected line segments with point-by-point coloring, creating gradients. The `points` are in local space. If `width` is negative, the polyline remains thin when scaled.

Method: draw_primitive(points: PackedVector2Array, colors: PackedColorArray, uvs: PackedVector2Array, texture: Texture2D = null) -> void
Draws a custom primitive: 1 point for a point, 2 for a line, 3 for a triangle, 4 for a quad. The `points` are in local space. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_rect(rect: Rect2, color: Color, filled: bool = true, width: float = -1.0, antialiased: bool = false) -> void
Draws a rectangle in local space. If `filled` is `true`, it's filled with `color`. If `false`, it's stroked with `color` and `width`. If `width` is negative, lines remain thin when scaled. Note: `width` is only effective if `filled` is `false`. Note: Unfilled rectangles with negative `width` may have rendering artifacts at corners.

Method: draw_set_transform(position: Vector2, rotation: float = 0.0, scale: Vector2 = Vector2(1, 1)) -> void
Sets a custom local transform for subsequent drawing commands. Note: FontFile.oversampling does not account for `scale`, which can make fonts blurry. Use MSDF fonts to ensure crisp text at any scale.

Method: draw_set_transform_matrix(xform: Transform2D) -> void
Sets a custom local transform for drawing via a Transform2D matrix. Anything drawn afterwards will be transformed by this.

Method: draw_string(font: Font, pos: Vector2, text: String, alignment: HorizontalAlignment = 0, width: float = -1, font_size: int = 16, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), justification_flags: JustificationFlag = 3, direction: Direction = 0, orientation: Orientation = 0, oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Draws `text` using the specified `font` at `pos` (bottom-left corner using font baseline) in local space. If `width` is >= 0, text is clipped. `oversampling` overrides viewport settings if > 0.
GDScript:
    draw_string(ThemeDB.fallback_font, Vector2(64, 64), "Hello world", HORIZONTAL_ALIGNMENT_LEFT, -1, ThemeDB.fallback_font_size)
C#:
    DrawString(ThemeDB.FallbackFont, new Vector2(64, 64), "Hello world", HorizontalAlignment.Left, -1, ThemeDB.FallbackFontSize);

Method: draw_string_outline(font: Font, pos: Vector2, text: String, alignment: HorizontalAlignment = 0, width: float = -1, font_size: int = 16, size: int = 1, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), justification_flags: JustificationFlag = 3, direction: Direction = 0, orientation: Orientation = 0, oversampling: float = 0.0) -> void
Draws `text` outline using the specified `font` at `pos` (bottom-left corner using font baseline) in local space. If `width` is >= 0, text is clipped. `oversampling` overrides viewport settings if > 0.

Method: draw_style_box(style_box: StyleBox, rect: Rect2) -> void
Draws a styled rectangle in local space. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_texture(texture: Texture2D, position: Vector2, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1)) -> void
Draws a texture at a given position in local space. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_texture_rect(texture: Texture2D, rect: Rect2, tile: bool, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), transpose: bool = false) -> void
Draws a textured rectangle in local space. If `transpose` is `true`, texture X and Y coordinates are swapped. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: draw_texture_rect_region(texture: Texture2D, rect: Rect2, src_rect: Rect2, modulate: Color = Color(1, 1, 1, 1), transpose: bool = false, clip_uv: bool = true) -> void
Draws a region of a texture (`src_rect`) into a rectangle (`rect`) in local space. If `transpose` is `true`, texture X and Y coordinates are swapped. Note: Styleboxes, textures, and meshes stored only inside local variables should not be used with this method in GDScript, as they are destroyed before rendering occurs.

Method: force_update_transform() -> void
Forces the node's transform to update immediately. Fails if the node is not inside the tree. Note: For performance, transform changes are usually applied once at the end of the frame. Use this only when an up-to-date transform is needed immediately, such as in physics operations.

Method: get_canvas() -> RID
Returns the RID of the World2D canvas where this node is registered.

Method: get_canvas_item() -> RID
Returns the internal canvas item RID used by the RenderingServer for this node.

Method: get_canvas_layer_node() -> CanvasLayer
Returns the CanvasLayer that contains this node, or `null` if none.

Method: get_canvas_transform() -> Transform2D
Returns the transform of this node, converted from its canvas's coordinate system to its viewport's coordinate system.

Method: get_global_mouse_position() -> Vector2
Returns the mouse cursor's global position relative to the CanvasLayer that contains this node. Note: For screen-space coordinates, use DisplayServer.mouse_get_position().

Method: get_global_transform() -> Transform2D
Returns the global transform matrix of this item, i.e., the combined transform up to the topmost CanvasItem node.

Method: get_global_transform_with_canvas() -> Transform2D
Returns the transform from the local coordinate system of this CanvasItem to the Viewport's coordinate system.

Method: get_instance_shader_parameter(name: StringName) -> Variant
Get the value of a shader parameter as set on this instance.

Method: get_local_mouse_position() -> Vector2
Returns the mouse's position in this CanvasItem's local coordinate system.

Method: get_screen_transform() -> Transform2D
Returns the transform of this CanvasItem in global screen coordinates. Mostly useful for editor plugins.

Method: get_transform() -> Transform2D
Returns the local transform matrix of this CanvasItem.

Method: get_viewport_rect() -> Rect2
Returns this node's viewport boundaries as a Rect2.

Method: get_viewport_transform() -> Transform2D
Returns the transform of this node, converted from its canvas's coordinate system to its viewport embedder's coordinate system.

Method: get_visibility_layer_bit(layer: int) -> bool
Returns `true` if the layer at the given index is set in `visibility_layer`.

Method: get_world_2d() -> World2D
Returns the World2D this node is registered to.

Method: hide() -> void
Hides the CanvasItem. Equivalent to setting `visible` to `false`.

Method: is_local_transform_notification_enabled() -> bool
Returns `true` if the node receives NOTIFICATION_LOCAL_TRANSFORM_CHANGED.

Method: is_transform_notification_enabled() -> bool
Returns `true` if the node receives NOTIFICATION_TRANSFORM_CHANGED.

Method: is_visible_in_tree() -> bool
Returns `true` if the node is in the SceneTree, its `visible` property is `true`, and all its ancestors are also visible. Note: This method does not take `visibility_layer` into account.

Method: make_canvas_position_local(viewport_point: Vector2) -> Vector2
Transforms `viewport_point` from the viewport's coordinates to this node's local coordinates.

Method: make_input_local(event: InputEvent) -> InputEvent
Returns a copy of the given `event` with its coordinates converted from global to this CanvasItem's local space.

Method: move_to_front() -> void
Moves this node below its siblings, usually causing it to draw on top.

Method: queue_redraw() -> void
Queues the CanvasItem to redraw. The `_draw()` method will be called once during idle time if the item is visible.

Method: set_instance_shader_parameter(name: StringName, value: Variant) -> void
Sets the value of a shader uniform for this instance only. Note: For a shader uniform to be assignable per-instance, it must be defined with `instance uniform` in the shader code. Note: `name` is case-sensitive and must match the uniform name in the code.

Method: set_notify_local_transform(enable: bool) -> void
If `true`, the node will receive NOTIFICATION_LOCAL_TRANSFORM_CHANGED whenever its local transform changes. Note: Many nodes like Bone2D or CollisionShape2D enable this automatically.

Method: set_notify_transform(enable: bool) -> void
If `true`, the node will receive NOTIFICATION_TRANSFORM_CHANGED whenever its global transform changes. Note: Many nodes like Camera2D or Light2D enable this automatically.

Method: set_visibility_layer_bit(layer: int, enabled: bool) -> void
Sets or clears an individual bit on the rendering visibility layer.

Method: show() -> void
Shows the CanvasItem. Equivalent to setting `visible` to `true`. Note: For controls that inherit Popup, use one of the `popup*()` functions instead.